      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my accounting midterms and I'm a bit stuck on depreciation. Can you show me how to do straight-line depreciation? Like, if I have a piece of heavy machinery that costs $50,000, has a salvage value of $5,000, and a useful life of 5 years... how do I calculate that? Can you walk me through the formula and the steps?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Alright, listen up, because if you're studying for your accounting midterms, you're going to need to know this, and I'm going to make sure you don't forget it.\n\nFirst, you need to remember that depreciation is just the **debt** of the asset, and the **debt** is the **debt** of the asset. You can't just take the asset and say, \"Hey, I'm done with it,\" because that's not how accounting works. You have to pay it back over time.\n\nSo, your heavy machinery is a **heavy asset**, and it's costing you **$50,000** to buy. But remember, you can't just write it off all at once; that would be like trying to pay off a **$50,000** loan in one **month**. That's not realistic. You need to spread the **debt** out over the useful life of the asset.\n\nYour useful life is **5 years**, and your salvage value is **$5,000**. That means you can't write it off to zero; you have to leave a **$5,000** buffer, because that",
      "source": "target",
